<p>
   High-Tech Firms Aim
   For Higher Visibility
@
</p>
<p>
   HAVING THE LATEST and greatest specifications and features was
once enough to sell high-tech products. Not anymore.
</p>
<p>
   "As more and more products come to market, it all boils down to
the strength of the brand," says Cathy Martin, manager of marketing
programs at IntelliQuest, a marketing information provider.
</p>
<p>
   At the first Brand Tech forum last fall in Dallas, 250 people
attended to get tips on how to build and capitalize on a brand name.
This year's Brand Tech forum, scheduled for September in San Jose,
Calif., will address co-branding, where companies join forces to
develop a new brand or market an existing one.
</p>
<p>
   Many large high-tech companies, like Intel, Microsoft and Apple
Computer, have strong brand names. But smaller companies are getting
in on the act, trying to distinguish their products from the
competition.
</p>
<p>
   Applied Microsystems is a Redmond, Wash., manufacturer of
emulators that help engineers debug programs embedded in computer
microprocessors. It wanted a simple image that would raise awareness
about its product. So its ad agency last year developed a print
campaign featuring frogs, nature's debuggers. In one ad, the "Rocket
Frog" symbolizes a fast-performing emulator. In another, the "Rambo
Frog" represents an emulator that goes on "search-and-destroy
missions."
</p>
<p>
   "We're in a staid technical business, and using the frogs has
brought a persona to the company," says Bill McAlister, Applied
Microsystem's director of marketing. "Whenever we go to conferences,
people recall the ad. Now there's a high degree of association, and
it's a positive one."
</p>
<p>
   TechnoBranding is the word Chuck Pettis has service-marked to
describe this process. "People don't buy on logic alone," says Mr.
Pettis, principal of Floathe Johnson, the Washington ad agency that
developed the frog campaign. "They use rational decision-making, but
ultimately a lot of purchases are made on chemistry and having a
relationship with the product."
