<p>
   City Buses Becoming
   Billboards on Wheels
@
</p>
<p>
   ADVERTISERS HAVE found a new twist on an old promotional vehicle.
</p>
<p>
   They're covering buses in 11 cities from headlight to taillight
in huge painted or vinyl ads that practically encase the bus.
</p>
<p>
   The vehicles have the advertising value of a blimp, the impact of
a billboard and the market penetration of a bus, according to
Transportation Displays, the New York City company marketing the
concept.
</p>
<p>
   Using a patented technique, the bus windows are covered by a
transparent material that is then painted. Passengers can see out,
but pedestrians and motorists can't see in. What they do see is a
rolling mural.
</p>
<p>
   The Phoenix Suns rented exterior space on five city buses to
advertise the basketball team's 25th anniversary. One of the more
attention-getting buses sported a glowering picture of star player
Charles Barkley. "We got a lot of calls from parents and other
people wanting to know what routes the painted buses were on so they
could ride or look for them," says Andrea Han, a spokeswoman for the
Phoenix transit authority. "These were the same buses on the inside
but people specifically wanted to know where they could catch the
`Charles Barkley' bus."
</p>
<p>
   Buying bus space is usually part of a broader marketing campaign,
says Jim Edwards, a senior account executive with the Cerine Coyne
ad agency in New York City.
</p>
<p>
   "There's no way to track whether we're getting direct results or
not, but it's another way to keep our clients top of mind," Mr.
Edwards says.
